04752nam a22007575i 9781442684416DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426844167 a10.3138/97814426844162doi  a(DE-B1597)464009  a(OCoLC)944177195  a(OCoLC)999354359  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB3279.H49bR32 2007eb 7aPHI0180002bisacsh04a1931 aRadloff, Bernhard, eauthor.10aHeidegger and the Question of National Socialism :bDisclosure and Gestalt /cBernhard Radloff. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2007  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Studies in Phenomenology and Hermeneutics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Challenge of the Planetary -- t2. Rhetoric and the Public Sphere -- t3. Heidegger and the Conservative Revolution -- t4. Volk, Work, and Historicity in Heidegger's Logik of 1934 -- t5. An Introduction to Metaphysics and Heidegger's Critique of 'Intellectualism' -- t6. Heidegger and Carl Schmitt: The Historicity of the Political -- t7. The Beiträge zur Philosophie and the Differentiation of Being -- tConclusion: Imperial Truth and Planetary Order -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe question of being was integral to the philosophy of Martin Heidegger (1889?1976) and was a large factor in the development of his political and aesthetic thought. In Heidegger and the Question of National Socialism, Bernhard Radloff investigates the philosophical foundations and cultural context of Heidegger?s conception of being, focusing on the idea of gestalt as the guiding thread that determined German conservative thought throughout the 1930s. In doing so, Heidegger?s philosophy is related to the whole of German society at the time, a society in which gestalt was the guiding light and the ultimate aspiration of artists, technicians, and politicians.Throughout the book, Heidegger?s own understanding of gestalt is used as a window to his thoughts on being, which is conceived of as incorporated, finite, and historically situated in beings. Concentrating on the years between 1933 and 1942, Radloff seeks to capture the response of Heidegger?s philosophy to National Socialism, examining key works and relating them to the literature of the German conservative revolution. Heidegger and the Question of National Socialism is, therefore a thorough treatment of his political philosophy as it relates to the question of being.Adopting both a historical and phenomenological approach to the subject, this book is equally an examination of German conservative ideology, a critique of technological determinism, and a study of one of the most controversial philosophers of twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aNational socialism and philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442684416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442684416.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK